{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "Welcome to Fluid Framework",
  "description": "A guided orientation to the Fluid Framework monorepo — repo structure, build system, key packages, and development workflow.",
  "isPrimary": true,
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "package.json",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "Monorepo Root",
      "description": "This is the root `package.json` for the **client release group** — the primary release group in this monorepo. The repo uses **pnpm** as its package manager and **fluid-build** as its build orchestrator.\n\nKey scripts:\n- `pnpm build` — build all packages\n- `pnpm test` — run all tests\n- `fluid-build .` — build only the current package and its dependencies (much faster)"
    },
    {
      "directory": "packages",
      "title": "Core Packages",
      "description": "The `packages/` directory contains the core Fluid Framework packages, organized into subdirectories by area:\n\n- **dds/** — Distributed Data Structures (SharedMap, SharedString, SharedTree, etc.)\n- **runtime/** — Container and data store runtime\n- **loader/** — Container loader and driver utilities\n- **drivers/** — Service drivers (Routerlicious, ODSP, local)\n- **framework/** — Higher-level framework APIs\n- **service-clients/** — Client libraries for Fluid services\n- **tools/** — Developer tooling\n- **test/** — Cross-cutting test utilities"
    },
    {
      "directory": "packages/dds",
      "title": "Distributed Data Structures (DDS)",
      "description": "This is the heart of Fluid Framework. Each DDS is a replicated data structure that synchronizes across clients using operational transforms or CRDTs.\n\nKey packages:\n- **tree/** — SharedTree, the primary DDS for hierarchical data\n- **map/** — SharedMap for key-value storage\n- **sequence/** — SharedString for collaborative text\n- **counter/** — SharedCounter for atomic counters\n- **matrix/** — SharedMatrix for 2D data"
    },
    {
      "directory": "packages/runtime",
      "title": "Runtime Layer",
      "description": "The runtime layer manages the lifecycle of containers and data stores:\n\n- **container-runtime/** — Manages the container lifecycle, op processing, and summarization\n- **datastore/** — Base implementation for Fluid data stores\n- **id-compressor/** — Efficient ID allocation across distributed clients\n- **container-runtime-definitions/** and **datastore-definitions/** — Public API interfaces"
    },
    {
      "directory": "server",
      "title": "Server (Routerlicious)",
      "description": "The `server/` directory contains **Routerlicious**, the reference Fluid relay service. It handles op ordering, storage, and distribution.\n\nFor local development, you'll typically use **Tinylicious** (a lightweight local server) rather than running the full Routerlicious stack. Port 7070 is pre-forwarded in the devcontainer for Tinylicious."
    },
    {
      "directory": "build-tools",
      "title": "Build Tools",
      "description": "Internal tooling for building, testing, and releasing Fluid packages:\n\n- **fluid-build** — Incremental build orchestrator that understands the dependency graph\n- **ESLint configs** — Shared linting rules for the monorepo\n- **Release tooling** — Version bumping, changelog generation, and release automation\n\nThis directory is its own release group with a separate `pnpm-workspace.yaml`."
    },
    {
      "directory": "examples",
      "title": "Examples",
      "description": "Example applications and benchmarks demonstrating Fluid Framework usage:\n\n- **apps/** — Full example applications\n- **benchmarks/** — Performance benchmarks\n- **data-objects/** — Example data objects and patterns\n- **version-migration/** — Examples of schema migration patterns\n\nThese are great for understanding how the pieces fit together."
    },
    {
      "file": ".devcontainer/ai-agent/devcontainer.json",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "Your Codespace Configuration",
      "description": "This is the devcontainer configuration for the **AI-enabled** profile you're using. It includes:\n\n- **Agency CLI** — run AI agents (Claude, GitHub Copilot) from the terminal\n- **Repoverlay** — overlay system for context files (agents, skills)\n- **GitHub CLI** and **SSH** — PR workflows and `gh codespace ssh` access\n- **ADO Codespaces Auth** — authenticate to Azure DevOps\n- **32 CPUs / 64 GB RAM** — higher compute than the Standard profile\n\n**First-time note:** Expect up to a dozen authentication prompts when you first create this codespace. Keep clicking through — they will end.\n\nIf agency is not already installed, run: `pnpm install:agency`\n\nFor full documentation, see the [AI-enabled Codespace wiki](https://github.com/microsoft/FluidFramework/wiki/AI%E2%80%90enabled-Codespace)."
    },
    {
      "file": ".devcontainer/ai-agent/GETTING_STARTED.md",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "AI Agent Aliases",
      "description": "This getting-started guide has the full list of AI agent aliases available in your terminal:\n\n**Claude:** `claude`, `haiku`, `sonnet`, `opus`, `nori`\n**Copilot:** `copilot`, `copilot-ado`, `copilot-kusto`, `copilot-oce`, `copilot-work`\n\nYou can also connect to this codespace from your local terminal via SSH:\n```\ngh codespace ssh\n```\n\nThis lets you run AI agents locally while the Codespace provides compute and repo context."
    },
    {
      "file": "DEV.md",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "Next Steps",
      "description": "You're all set! Here's what to do next:\n\n1. Run `pnpm install` if dependencies aren't already installed\n2. Navigate to the package you want to work on\n3. Run `fluid-build .` to build it and its dependencies\n4. Run `pnpm test` to verify things work\n5. Use `claude` or `nori` to get AI assistance\n\nThis file (`DEV.md`) has the full development setup guide.\n\nFor more info on the AI-enabled codespace, see the [wiki](https://github.com/microsoft/FluidFramework/wiki/AI%E2%80%90enabled-Codespace)."
    }
  ]
}
